Exercise 16.1: Define instantiation.

Answer:
Instantiation is the process of creating a new instance of the a template using it's arguments rather then parameters.

Exercise 16.9: What is a function template? What is a class template?

Answer:
Function template - is a blueprint for the same function for different types.
Class template - is a blueprint for classes.

Exercise 16.10: What happens when a class template is instantiated?

Answer:
The compiler uses  the template arguments in order to create a class instance of that argument.

Exercise 16.11: The following definition of List is incorrect. How would you fix it?

template <typename elemType> class ListItem;
template <typename elemType> class List {
    public:
        List<elemType>();
        List<elemType>(const List<elemType> &);
        List<elemType>& operator=(const List<elemType> &);
        ~List();
        void insert(ListItem *ptr, elemType value);
    private:
        ListItem *front, *end;
};

Answer:
The current definition is incorrect due to the following lines:
void insert(ListItem *ptr, elemType value); - Because ListItem requires a type this line should
be change to --> void insert(ListItem<elemType> *ptr, elemType value);
Second line:
ListItem *front, *end; - Because ListItem requires a type, this line should be changed to:
ListItem<elemType> *front, *end;

Exercise 16.17: What, if any, are the differences between a type parameter
that is declared as a typename and one that is declared as a class? When
must typename be used?

Answer:
Overall there no major differences however only typename supports using the scope operator.
Typename must be used when we want to use a type member of a template parameter type.

Exercise 16.18: Explain each of the following function template declarations
and identify whether any are illegal. Correct each error that you find.

(a) template <typename T, U, typename V> void f1(T, U, V);
(b) template <typename T> T f2(int &T);
(c) inline template <typename T> T foo(T, unsigned int*);
(d) template <typename T> f4(T, T);
(e) typedef char Ctype;
    template <typename Ctype> Ctype f5(Ctype a);

Answer:
a) Declaration of template with 3 parameters --> Illegal since U is declared without a type.
Fix:
template <typename T, typename U, typename V> void f1(T, U, V);
b) Declaration of template with a single template parameter named T --> Illegal since argument name T over shadows the
template parameter.
Fix:
template <typename T> T f2(int &T1);
c)Declaration of template with a single template parameter --> Illegal since inline should appear after the
template parameter.
Fix:
template <typename T> inline T foo(T, unsigned int*);
d) Declaration of template with single template parameter --> Illegal since f4 doesn't have return type.
Fix:
template <typename T> void f4(T, T);
e) Declaration of template with single template parameter --> Legal, but Ctype will be overshadowed by
the template parameter.